let _markdown = "\n\n# Hi-C Mode CLI\n\nHi-C mode analyzes genome-wide chromatin architecture using proximity ligation sequencing. This mode generates contact matrices at multiple resolutions using pairtools and cooler.\n\n## Overview\n\nHi-C captures all chromatin interactions genome-wide without protein-specific enrichment. The Chr3D pipeline:\n\n1. **Genomic Mapping** - Maps paired-end reads using BWA-MEM\n2. **Pairtools Processing** - Parses, sorts, deduplicates, and filters pairs\n3. **Cooler Matrix Generation** - Creates multi-resolution contact matrices (.mcool)\n4. **QC Statistics** - Generates comprehensive quality metrics\n\n**Note**: Hi-C mode does **not** include peak calling or loop calling (no protein enrichment).\n\n## Command\n\n```bash\nchr3d run --mode hic [options]\n```\n\n## Required Arguments\n\n| Argument         | Description                               |\n| ---------------- | ----------------------------------------- |\n| `--fastq-r1`     | Input R1 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)   |\n| `--fastq-r2`     | Input R2 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)   |\n| `--genome-index` | BWA-indexed reference genome FASTA        |\n| `--chrom-sizes`  | Chromosome sizes file (required for Hi-C) |\n| `--output-dir`   | Output directory                          |\n\n## Optional Arguments\n\n| Argument               | Default           | Description                                        |\n| ---------------------- | ----------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |\n| `--threads`            | 24                | Number of threads                                  |\n| `--mapping-quality`    | 30                | Minimum mapping quality                            |\n| `--min-distance`       | 1000              | Minimum distance for valid pairs (bp)              |\n| `--resolution`         | `1000,5000,10000` | Resolutions for contact matrices (comma-separated) |\n| `--assembly`           | `hg38`            | Genome assembly name                               |\n| `--sample-id`          | `sample`          | Sample identifier                                  |\n| `--keep-intermediates` | False             | Keep intermediate files                            |\n\n## Complete Example\n\n```bash\nchr3d run --mode hic \\\n    --fastq-r1 /data/HiC_sample_R1.fastq.gz \\\n    --fastq-r2 /data/HiC_sample_R2.fastq.gz \\\n    --genome-index /ref/hg38.fa \\\n    --chrom-sizes /ref/hg38.chrom.sizes \\\n    --output-dir /output/hic_analysis \\\n    --threads 16 \\\n    --mapping-quality 30 \\\n    --min-distance 1000 \\\n    --resolution 1000,5000,10000,25000,50000,100000 \\\n    --assembly hg38 \\\n    --sample-id HiC_experiment \\\n    --keep-intermediates\n```\n\n## Generating Chromosome Sizes File\n\nIf you don't have a chromosome sizes file:\n\n```bash\n# Using samtools\nsamtools faidx /ref/hg38.fa\ncut -f1,2 /ref/hg38.fa.fai > /ref/hg38.chrom.sizes\n\n# Or download from UCSC\nwget https://hgdownload.soe.ucsc.edu/goldenPath/hg38/bigZips/hg38.chrom.sizes\n```\n\n## Pipeline Steps\n\n### Step 1: BWA-MEM Alignment\n\nMaps paired-end reads to reference genome.\n\n```\nInput:  sample_R1.fastq.gz, sample_R2.fastq.gz\nOutput: aligned/sample.bam\n```\n\n**Alignment Statistics:**\n\n* Total read pairs\n* Mapped reads\n* Mapping quality distribution\n\n### Step 2: Pairtools Parse\n\nConverts aligned BAM to pairs format with interaction classification.\n\n```\nInput:  aligned/sample.bam\nOutput: pairs/sample.pairs.gz\n```\n\n**Pair Types:**\n\n* `UU`: Both reads uniquely mapped\n* `UR/RU`: One unique, one rescued\n* `MU/UM`: One multi-mapped\n* `MM`: Both multi-mapped\n* `NN`: Both unmapped\n\n### Step 3: Pairtools Sort\n\nSorts pairs by genomic coordinates.\n\n```\nInput:  pairs/sample.pairs.gz\nOutput: pairs/sample.sorted.pairs.gz\n```\n\n### Step 4: Pairtools Dedup\n\nRemoves PCR duplicates.\n\n```\nInput:  pairs/sample.sorted.pairs.gz\nOutput: pairs/sample.dedup.pairs.gz\n```\n\n**Deduplication Statistics:**\n\n* Total pairs\n* Unique pairs\n* Duplicate rate\n\n### Step 5: Pairtools Select\n\nFilters for valid cis pairs above minimum distance.\n\n```\nInput:  pairs/sample.dedup.pairs.gz\nOutput: pairs/sample.filtered.pairs.gz\n```\n\n**Filtering Criteria:**\n\n* Cis pairs only (same chromosome)\n* Distance ≥ `--min-distance`\n* Mapping quality ≥ `--mapping-quality`\n\n### Step 6: Cooler Matrix Generation\n\nCreates multi-resolution contact matrices.\n\n```\nInput:  pairs/sample.filtered.pairs.gz\nOutput: matrices/sample.mcool\n```\n\n**Resolutions:**\n\n* Default: 1kb, 5kb, 10kb\n* Custom: Use `--resolution` flag\n\n## Output Files\n\n```\noutput_dir/\n├── aligned/\n│   └── sample.bam\n├── pairs/\n│   ├── sample.pairs.gz\n│   ├── sample.sorted.pairs.gz\n│   ├── sample.dedup.pairs.gz\n│   └── sample.filtered.pairs.gz\n├── matrices/\n│   └── sample.mcool\n├── processed/\n│   └── sample.valid_pairs.txt\n└── qc/\n    ├── sample_pairs.stats\n    ├── sample_dedup.stats\n    └── sample_summary.txt\n```\n\n## Output Formats\n\n### Pairs Format (.pairs.gz)\n\nStandard 4DN pairs format:\n\n```\n## pairs format v1.0\n#columns: readID chr1 pos1 chr2 pos2 strand1 strand2 pair_type\nread1   chr1    1000    chr1    5000    +   -   UU\nread2   chr1    2000    chr2    3000    +   +   UU\n```\n\n### Cooler Format (.mcool)\n\nMulti-resolution cooler file containing:\n\n* Contact matrices at each resolution\n* Bin annotations\n* Chromosome information\n\n**Accessing with Python:**\n\n```python\nimport cooler\n\n# Load specific resolution\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\")\n\n# Get matrix for region\nmatrix = clr.matrix(balance=False).fetch(\"chr1:1000000-2000000\")\n```\n\n### QC Statistics\n\nThe `qc/sample_pairs.stats` file contains:\n\n| Metric            | Description                |\n| ----------------- | -------------------------- |\n| total             | Total read pairs           |\n| total\\_mapped     | Successfully mapped pairs  |\n| total\\_dups       | Duplicate pairs            |\n| total\\_nodups     | Unique pairs               |\n| cis               | Same-chromosome pairs      |\n| trans             | Different-chromosome pairs |\n| cis\\_1kb+         | Cis pairs >1kb apart       |\n| cis\\_10kb+        | Cis pairs >10kb apart      |\n| summary/frac\\_cis | Fraction of cis pairs      |\n\n## Quality Metrics\n\n**Good Hi-C Data:**\n\n| Metric         | Good  | Acceptable | Poor  |\n| -------------- | ----- | ---------- | ----- |\n| Mapping rate   | >90%  | 70-90%     | \\<70% |\n| Cis ratio      | >60%  | 40-60%     | \\<40% |\n| Cis >10kb      | >40%  | 20-40%     | \\<20% |\n| Duplicate rate | \\<20% | 20-40%     | >40%  |\n\n**Interpreting Results:**\n\n* **High trans ratio**: May indicate random ligation or contamination\n* **Low cis >10kb**: Short-range bias, may need optimization\n* **High duplicate rate**: Low library complexity\n\n## Resolution Guidelines\n\n| Resolution | Use Case          | Memory   |\n| ---------- | ----------------- | -------- |\n| 1kb        | Fine-scale loops  | High     |\n| 5kb        | Loop detection    | Medium   |\n| 10kb       | TAD calling       | Medium   |\n| 25kb       | Compartments      | Low      |\n| 50kb       | Overview          | Low      |\n| 100kb      | Whole-genome view | Very Low |\n\n**Recommendations:**\n\n* Loop calling: 5-10kb\n* TAD calling: 10-25kb\n* Compartment analysis: 25-100kb\n* Visualization: Multiple resolutions\n\n## Downstream Analysis\n\n### With Cooler/Cooltools\n\n```bash\n# Balance matrix (ICE normalization)\ncooler balance sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\n\n# Call TADs\ncooltools insulation sample.mcool::resolutions/10000 \\\n    --window-pixels 10 \\\n    -o sample_insulation.tsv\n\n# Call compartments\ncooltools eigs-cis sample.mcool::resolutions/100000 \\\n    --phasing-track gc_content.bw \\\n    -o sample_compartments\n```\n\n### With HiCExplorer\n\n```bash\n# Convert to h5 format\nhicConvertFormat -m sample.mcool::resolutions/10000 \\\n    -o sample.h5 --inputFormat cool --outputFormat h5\n\n# Find TADs\nhicFindTADs -m sample.h5 \\\n    --outPrefix sample_tads \\\n    --correctForMultipleTesting fdr\n```\n\n### With Juicer Tools\n\n```bash\n# Convert to .hic format\njava -jar juicer_tools.jar pre \\\n    sample.filtered.pairs.gz \\\n    sample.hic \\\n    hg38.chrom.sizes\n```\n\n## Hi-C vs HiChIP vs ChIA-PET\n\n| Feature      | Hi-C           | HiChIP           | ChIA-PET         |\n| ------------ | -------------- | ---------------- | ---------------- |\n| Enrichment   | None           | ChIP             | ChIP             |\n| Interactions | All            | Protein-specific | Protein-specific |\n| Resolution   | Genome-wide    | Focused          | Focused          |\n| Input cells  | 1-10M          | 1M               | 100M             |\n| Loop calling | External tools | Built-in         | Built-in         |\n| Peak calling | No             | Yes              | Yes              |\n\n## Tips\n\n1. **Sequencing Depth**: Aim for >500M read pairs for 1kb resolution\n2. **Chromosome Sizes**: Must match your reference genome exactly\n3. **Memory**: High resolutions require significant RAM (>64GB for 1kb)\n4. **Storage**: .mcool files can be large (10-100GB)\n5. **Normalization**: Use `cooler balance` for downstream analysis\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### Low cis ratio\n\n* Check for contamination\n* Verify ligation efficiency\n* May indicate protocol issues\n\n### High duplicate rate\n\n* Increase library complexity\n* Sequence deeper\n* Optimize PCR cycles\n\n### Memory errors\n\n* Reduce resolution\n* Increase available RAM\n* Process chromosomes separately\n\n### Cooler errors\n\n* Verify chromosome sizes file format\n* Check pairs file integrity\n* Ensure sufficient disk space\n";
